1
00:00:36,049 --> 00:00:38,984
<i>[ Woman ] My favorite children's book</i>
<i>is about a little prince...</i>

2
00:00:39,052 --> 00:00:42,112
<i>who came to Earth from a distant asteroid.</i>

3
00:00:42,189 --> 00:00:46,125
<i>He meets a pilot</i>
<i>whose plane has crashed in a desert.</i>

4
00:00:46,193 --> 00:00:49,128
<i>The little prince teaches the pilot many things...</i>

5
00:00:49,196 --> 00:00:51,528
<i>but mainly about love.</i>

6
00:00:51,598 --> 00:00:54,567
<i>My father always told me</i>
<i>I was like the little prince.</i>

7
00:00:54,635 --> 00:00:56,569
<i>But after I met Adam...</i>

8
00:00:56,637 --> 00:00:59,629
<i>I realized I was the pilot all along.</i>

9
00:01:20,060 --> 00:01:22,051
<i>[ Crunch ]</i>

10
00:03:47,808 --> 00:03:50,140
- Morning, Adam.
- Good morning, Kelli.

11
00:03:53,013 --> 00:03:55,982
- <i>Good morning, Lulu.</i>
- <i>[ Kelli's Voice ] Good morning, Adam.</i>

12
00:03:59,052 --> 00:04:00,986
[ Kelli's Voice ]
I don't know what to say.

13
00:04:01,054 --> 00:04:02,715
- [ Adam ] Say anything.
- Okay.

14
00:04:02,789 --> 00:04:05,883
Adam Raki is the cutest guy in the office.
How's that?

15
00:04:05,959 --> 00:04:07,722
- That's fine.
- Morning, Adam.

16
00:04:07,794 --> 00:04:10,786
- <i>[ Lulu ] Good morning, Mr. Klieber!</i>
- Morning, Kelli.

17
00:04:10,864 --> 00:04:13,890
- [ Chuckles ] Good morning.
- Good morning, Adam!

18
00:04:13,967 --> 00:04:15,594
- How did she do that?
- What?

19
00:04:15,669 --> 00:04:17,933
How did she know it was me
and then you talking?

20
00:04:18,004 --> 00:04:19,733
Voice recognition.

21
00:04:19,806 --> 00:04:24,505
I put in voice patterns from some people
and added SPLICE to the recognition system.

22
00:04:24,578 --> 00:04:29,208
SPLICE stands for "Stereo-based Piece-wise
Linear Compensation for Environment."

23
00:04:29,282 --> 00:04:31,614
- It's an algorithm that I placed–
- Adam. Adam.

24
00:04:31,685 --> 00:04:33,619
Did Chatty Patty have SPLICE?

25
00:04:33,687 --> 00:04:36,212
<i>Did Big Mouth Billy Bass have SPLICE?</i>

26
00:04:36,289 --> 00:04:38,655
But you said I could make her sound like Kelli.

27
00:04:38,725 --> 00:04:42,718
I said she could sound like Kelli.
I didn't say to give her free will.

28
00:04:42,796 --> 00:04:45,458
She doesn't have free will.

29
00:04:45,532 --> 00:04:50,196
5,000 at a hundred dollars,
not five at a thousand dollars<i>. Capisce?</i>

30
00:04:52,672 --> 00:04:56,073
- Good-bye, Mr. Klieber.
- [ Lulu ] Good-bye, Adam.

31
00:05:43,290 --> 00:05:46,350
<i>[ Man's Voice ]</i>
<i>All of which gives us the rare opportunity...</i>

32
00:05:46,426 --> 00:05:48,360
- [ Speaking Along ]
- to explore the mysterious terrain...

33
00:05:48,428 --> 00:05:51,727
that lies between fame and craft...

34
00:05:51,798 --> 00:05:55,757
between the public persona
and the private, precious self.

35
00:05:55,836 --> 00:05:59,203
Ladies and gentlemen,
the Actors Studio is proud to welcome...

36
00:05:59,272 --> 00:06:01,206
an actress we admire...

37
00:06:01,274 --> 00:06:03,139
Julia Roberts.

38
00:06:03,210 --> 00:06:05,201
[ Audience Applauding ]

39
00:06:12,152 --> 00:06:13,050
<i>[ Lock Rattling ]</i>

40
00:06:13,820 --> 00:06:15,811
Perfect.

41
00:06:18,358 --> 00:06:21,259
- Oh.
- Is this open?

42
00:06:22,629 --> 00:06:25,564
I mean, to residents. Do you have a key?

43
00:06:25,632 --> 00:06:27,896
Uh, yes.

44
00:06:27,968 --> 00:06:31,301
I just moved in. Beth Buchwald, 3A.

45
00:06:31,371 --> 00:06:33,430
Adam. Second floor. Two.

46
00:06:35,308 --> 00:06:37,208
You're not doing your laundry?

47
00:06:38,278 --> 00:06:41,247
Oh. Um, yeah.

48
00:06:41,314 --> 00:06:44,374
Looks like a bit of an emergency.

49
00:06:46,653 --> 00:06:49,247
Would you mind letting me in?

50
00:06:50,290 --> 00:06:52,781
- Uh, yeah. Yeah. Sure.
- Thanks.

51
00:06:56,997 --> 00:07:00,091
I mean, I loved it. Downtown's my hood.

52
00:07:00,166 --> 00:07:04,569
But this place is bigger
and it's right around the corner from Wildwood.

53
00:07:04,638 --> 00:07:07,402
Can you see the sky from the third floor?

54
00:07:07,474 --> 00:07:11,103
I guess I would if the windows
weren't covered in soot.

55
00:07:11,177 --> 00:07:13,441
Some nerve, right...

56
00:07:13,513 --> 00:07:16,778
calling a school in the middle of Manhattan
Wildwood?

57
00:07:16,850 --> 00:07:19,944
It's just temporary, actually.

58
00:07:20,020 --> 00:07:23,148
The job, not the name of the school.

59
00:07:23,223 --> 00:07:26,158
I'm a writer. For children.
So it's a good experience.

60
00:07:29,396 --> 00:07:30,829
What do you do?

61
00:07:30,897 --> 00:07:33,024
Uh, I help make toys.

62
00:07:33,099 --> 00:07:35,033
Oh, you're an elf?

63
00:07:35,101 --> 00:07:37,729
[ Laughs ]
No, I'm an electronic engineer.

64
00:07:37,804 --> 00:07:41,865
- <i>[ Clicking ]</i>
- Oh. You need a card for the wash.

65
00:07:41,942 --> 00:07:44,274
No, I've got one.

66
00:07:44,344 --> 00:07:48,280
Funny. I think I left mine upstairs in my packet.

67
00:07:48,348 --> 00:07:50,282
Could I borrow yours for now?

68
00:07:50,350 --> 00:07:52,341
Okay.

69
00:07:55,221 --> 00:07:57,382
[ Whispers ]
Oh. Right.

70
00:08:02,929 --> 00:08:04,920
Thanks.

71
00:08:06,800 --> 00:08:09,291
Good. Good work, Beth.

72
00:08:15,208 --> 00:08:17,369
Hi, neighbor.

73
00:08:17,444 --> 00:08:20,971
There are new images of Saturn
from the Cassini Project.

74
00:08:31,324 --> 00:08:32,916
Oh.

75
00:08:32,993 --> 00:08:34,688
God.

76
00:08:35,762 --> 00:08:38,322
<i>I always wish I knew more about space.</i>

77
00:08:38,398 --> 00:08:40,229
You did? Like what?

78
00:08:41,501 --> 00:08:44,800
I don't know. You know, what's out there.

79
00:08:46,172 --> 00:08:48,436
You have to narrow that down.

80
00:08:48,508 --> 00:08:50,442
[ Laughs ]
Yeah, I guess you're right.

81
00:08:50,510 --> 00:08:52,944
Well, I have books, telescopes, star charts.

82
00:08:53,013 --> 00:08:54,947
You could borrow some stuff.

83
00:08:55,015 --> 00:08:59,008
We could go out,
look at the sky... t-tonight.

84
00:08:59,085 --> 00:09:01,280
Maybe sometime. Sure.

85
00:09:02,355 --> 00:09:03,947
- Okay.
- [ Chuckles ]

86
00:09:06,059 --> 00:09:09,722
Well, I'll just be hauling these enormous
grocery bags upstairs now.

87
00:09:09,796 --> 00:09:11,889
Okay.

88
00:09:11,965 --> 00:09:13,557
Okay.

89
00:09:13,633 --> 00:09:15,294
[ Grunting ]

90
00:09:35,055 --> 00:09:37,046
[ Chattering ]

91
00:09:45,765 --> 00:09:47,756
What are you doing?

92
00:09:47,834 --> 00:09:49,597
Oh.

93
00:09:49,669 --> 00:09:51,432
People watching.

94
00:09:52,505 --> 00:09:54,769
Anyone in particular?

95
00:09:56,109 --> 00:09:58,577
Just people.

96
00:10:04,117 --> 00:10:08,645
Listen, I'm going out with some friends
tonight, later, if you want to come.

97
00:10:08,721 --> 00:10:10,655
Oh.

98
00:10:10,723 --> 00:10:14,090
<i>They're people,</i>
<i>so you might want to... watch them.</i>

99
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:16,321
Uh-huh.

100
00:10:16,396 --> 00:10:18,626
But if not, you know, that's fine.

101
00:10:18,698 --> 00:10:22,964
No, I want to go,
but, um, I– I-I don't think I can.

102
00:10:23,036 --> 00:10:25,971
- Okay, if you're busy.
- No.

103
00:10:26,039 --> 00:10:30,669
I mean, it's not a date. It's just a little
moving-in celebration, you know.

104
00:10:30,743 --> 00:10:32,301
When?

105
00:10:32,378 --> 00:10:34,812
8:00. 8:00-ish.

106
00:10:34,881 --> 00:10:36,815
Uh-huh.

107
00:10:36,883 --> 00:10:38,817
Look, there's no pressure.

108
00:10:38,885 --> 00:10:42,218
[ Laughs ] I'll just knock on your door
on my way out, and if you can, you can.

109
00:10:43,289 --> 00:10:45,120
- Okay.
- <i>Yeah?</i>

110
00:10:45,191 --> 00:10:46,852
- Yeah.
- <i>Okay.</i>

111
00:10:51,531 --> 00:10:54,523
<i>[ Loud Ticking ]</i>

112
00:11:10,884 --> 00:11:13,876
<i>[ Ticking Continues ]</i>

113
00:11:18,558 --> 00:11:21,550
<i>[ Ticking Continues ]</i>

114
00:11:24,731 --> 00:11:27,723
<i>[ Footsteps ]</i>

115
00:11:29,235 --> 00:11:31,226
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

116
00:11:40,079 --> 00:11:41,706
Adam?

117
00:11:41,781 --> 00:11:43,772
<i>[ Ticking Continues ]</i>

118
00:11:43,850 --> 00:11:45,784
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

119
00:11:45,852 --> 00:11:47,342
<i>Adam.</i>

120
00:11:52,592 --> 00:11:55,584
<i>[ Footsteps ]</i>

121
00:12:20,053 --> 00:12:22,044
- <i>[ Woman ] See you later!</i>
- <i>[ Beth ] Good night!</i>

122
00:12:22,121 --> 00:12:24,112
<i>[ Door Opening ]</i>

123
00:12:28,828 --> 00:12:31,820
I-I'm sorry I didn't come out with your friends.

124
00:12:31,898 --> 00:12:33,798
No problem.

125
00:12:34,867 --> 00:12:36,892
I get kind of overloaded.

126
00:12:39,172 --> 00:12:41,538
I have something to show you.

127
00:12:44,377 --> 00:12:46,368
Come in. Come in.

128
00:12:49,649 --> 00:12:51,640
<i>[ Switch Clicks ]</i>

129
00:12:51,718 --> 00:12:53,845
Oh, my!

130
00:12:57,824 --> 00:13:00,452
<i>You said you want to know more about space.</i>

131
00:13:01,894 --> 00:13:04,761
<i>Because it looks like this</i>
<i>people think of it as still...</i>

132
00:13:04,831 --> 00:13:06,765
<i>even though we know its expanding.</i>

133
00:13:06,833 --> 00:13:09,768
<i>All parts of the universe</i>
<i>are moving away from one another...</i>

134
00:13:09,836 --> 00:13:12,270
<i>most of them faster than the speed of light,</i>
<i>except for-</i>

135
00:13:12,338 --> 00:13:15,273
I thought nothing went faster
than the speed of light.

136
00:13:15,341 --> 00:13:19,334
<i>Right, right. Nothing goes</i>
through <i>space faster, but space itself g-</i>

137
00:13:19,412 --> 00:13:22,813
<i>Um, uh, do you know about the Big Bang?</i>

138
00:13:22,882 --> 00:13:26,045
A little. In the beginning, God crea–

139
00:13:26,119 --> 00:13:29,555
<i>The inflation theory says the Big Bang came</i>
<i>from as little as a 20-pound chunk of space...</i>

140
00:13:29,622 --> 00:13:31,385
about 14 billion years ago...

141
00:13:31,457 --> 00:13:35,393
<i>that expanded to the size of the universe</i>
<i>in 10 to the minus-39 seconds.</i>

142
00:13:35,461 --> 00:13:37,588
Ten to the minus-39?

143
00:13:37,664 --> 00:13:39,598
A decimal point, 39 zeros, and then a one.

144
00:13:39,666 --> 00:13:42,829
That's the fraction of a second
in which the universe was formed.

145
00:13:42,902 --> 00:13:45,370
<i>That's billions and billions of times</i>
<i>faster than light.</i>

146
00:13:45,438 --> 00:13:49,033
Ooh, that's... fast.

147
00:13:50,376 --> 00:13:52,037
Yeah.

148
00:13:55,248 --> 00:13:57,239
<i>[ Switch Clicks ]</i>

149
00:13:57,317 --> 00:13:59,182
Wow!

150
00:13:59,252 --> 00:14:03,211
Uh, these are all pictures of stars and galaxies
that have been traveling away from us...

151
00:14:03,289 --> 00:14:06,986
for hundreds of millions or billions of years.

152
00:14:07,060 --> 00:14:11,656
<i>But that's still nearby compared to</i>
<i>most of the universe that we'll never see.</i>

153
00:14:11,731 --> 00:14:13,562
Never?

154
00:14:13,633 --> 00:14:17,330
<i>Well, things that move apart faster than light</i>
<i>can't ever see one another...</i>

155
00:14:17,403 --> 00:14:19,701
because the light from one
never catches up to the other.

156
00:14:19,772 --> 00:14:21,706
<i>After the Big Bang...</i>

157
00:14:21,774 --> 00:14:24,265
the expansion of the universe slowed down.

158
00:14:24,344 --> 00:14:26,403
But then, after seven billion years...

159
00:14:26,479 --> 00:14:28,709
<i>for some reason it speeded up again...</i>

160
00:14:28,781 --> 00:14:31,113
<i>and it's been speeding up ever since.</i>

161
00:14:31,184 --> 00:14:35,245
Someday everything you see here
will disappear forever.

162
00:14:36,689 --> 00:14:38,623
<i>And eventually the night sky...</i>

163
00:14:38,691 --> 00:14:41,353
will be almost completely dark.

164
00:14:46,632 --> 00:14:49,226
That's kinda sad.

165
00:14:50,403 --> 00:14:52,064
Sad?

166
00:14:52,138 --> 00:14:53,571
Hmm.

167
00:14:57,844 --> 00:15:01,439
I-I have been talking too much, so–

168
00:15:01,514 --> 00:15:04,005
No, it's... fascinating.

169
00:15:04,083 --> 00:15:07,052
- But I talk too much when I get excited.
- No, really.

170
00:15:07,120 --> 00:15:09,054
It's– It's amazing.

171
00:15:09,122 --> 00:15:12,057
Well, I-I could tell you quickly
about M-brane theory.

172
00:15:12,125 --> 00:15:14,559
Oh, no, it's okay. Maybe next time.

173
00:15:14,627 --> 00:15:16,618
Okay. It's very speculative.

174
00:15:18,064 --> 00:15:19,827
Well, I should go.

175
00:15:22,602 --> 00:15:25,036
Good night, Beth.

176
00:15:25,104 --> 00:15:27,095
Good night.
[ Giggles ]

177
00:15:30,343 --> 00:15:33,676
Thanks. I love your planetarium.

178
00:15:33,746 --> 00:15:36,044
Oh. [ Laughs ] You're welcome.

179
00:15:43,156 --> 00:15:45,420
[ Both Laughing ]

180
00:15:46,459 --> 00:15:48,393
Oh, I could have waited, Daddy.

181
00:15:48,461 --> 00:15:51,396
Not another day.
I wanted you out of that rat trap for five years.

182
00:15:51,464 --> 00:15:54,922
- They were mice.
- But I was right, wasn't I? You love it.

183
00:15:55,001 --> 00:15:58,198
It's okay. It's not like the Village.
I've only met one person so far.

184
00:15:58,271 --> 00:16:01,206
- It's new.
- He did have a planetarium
in his living room though.

185
00:16:01,274 --> 00:16:03,139
You were in someone's living room.

186
00:16:03,209 --> 00:16:05,143
He's cute. He lives in the building.

187
00:16:05,211 --> 00:16:07,145
Whatever happened to Rich Lippmann?

188
00:16:07,213 --> 00:16:08,840
Not going there.

189
00:16:08,915 --> 00:16:12,180
But what was the name of his company?
Founder's Fund?

190
00:16:13,186 --> 00:16:14,813
Okay. Okay.

191
00:16:14,887 --> 00:16:17,287
So, your neighbor's an astronomer?

192
00:16:17,356 --> 00:16:20,291
No, he's an electronic engineer,
whatever that means.

193
00:16:20,359 --> 00:16:23,624
- But he hasn't even said hello to me
since the first time, so–
- So, he's an idiot.

194
00:16:23,696 --> 00:16:25,391
No, it's me.

195
00:16:25,465 --> 00:16:29,902
Didn't anyone tell you and Mom
that only children are emotional retards...

196
00:16:29,969 --> 00:16:33,200
spoilt, too trusting and unequipped to cope?

197
00:16:33,272 --> 00:16:35,206
What were you thinking?

198
00:16:35,274 --> 00:16:37,265
That we had one perfect child.

199
00:16:40,947 --> 00:16:42,414
How's school?

200
00:16:42,482 --> 00:16:44,575
We just started.

201
00:16:44,650 --> 00:16:47,915
"The course of civilization is a race
between catastrophe and education."

202
00:16:47,987 --> 00:16:50,547
- John F. Kennedy.
- I know.

203
00:16:50,623 --> 00:16:52,591
Well, if you marry an investment banker...

204
00:16:52,658 --> 00:16:54,592
you could do whatever you want.

205
00:16:54,660 --> 00:16:57,390
Rich Lippmann is a dick, Daddy.
Can we leave it at that?

206
00:16:57,463 --> 00:16:59,431
Don't say "dick" to your father.

207
00:16:59,499 --> 00:17:03,060
No one's perfect, Bethy. That's all I'm saying.

208
00:17:05,037 --> 00:17:08,234
<i>But their sensor systems have detected</i>
<i>an error in analyzing space radiation.</i>

209
00:17:08,307 --> 00:17:11,435
Adam, I'm having lunch.

210
00:17:11,511 --> 00:17:13,445
- Speak English.
- I'm sorry.

211
00:17:13,513 --> 00:17:15,447
You see, the Star Tracker system is–

212
00:17:15,515 --> 00:17:20,953
- No. No more background radiation
black holes or Mars robots.
- [ Stammering ]

213
00:17:21,020 --> 00:17:23,079
Lunchtime is for guy talk.

214
00:17:23,155 --> 00:17:27,683
Two guys talking about women,
the weather and such. You got it?

215
00:17:30,329 --> 00:17:32,889
- But the Star Tracker system–
- No.

216
00:17:38,271 --> 00:17:40,262
Hmm.
[ Chuckles ]

217
00:17:40,339 --> 00:17:42,273
A woman moved into 3A.

218
00:17:42,341 --> 00:17:45,401
All right. Now, <i>that's</i> lunch talk.

219
00:17:45,478 --> 00:17:47,912
So?

220
00:17:47,980 --> 00:17:49,914
So, that's all.

221
00:17:49,982 --> 00:17:53,349
Come on. A woman moved into 3A.

222
00:17:53,419 --> 00:17:55,546
She looked–

223
00:17:55,621 --> 00:17:57,555
She looked nice.

224
00:17:57,623 --> 00:18:00,091
Good. [ Laughs ] Good!

225
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:03,328
- Uh, you gonna meet her?
- I did.

226
00:18:03,396 --> 00:18:04,988
You did?

227
00:18:05,064 --> 00:18:08,056
We did laundry. She came to my apartment.

228
00:18:08,134 --> 00:18:11,069
- She did?
- Yeah, I told her something about space.

229
00:18:11,137 --> 00:18:14,072
- Oh, Jesus. How'd she take it?
- She liked it.

230
00:18:14,140 --> 00:18:15,573
She–

231
00:18:15,641 --> 00:18:18,633
Well, bless my stars. You gonna see her again?

232
00:18:18,711 --> 00:18:20,975
I see her almost every day.

233
00:18:21,047 --> 00:18:22,981
You talk to her again?

234
00:18:23,049 --> 00:18:25,449
No.

235
00:18:25,518 --> 00:18:27,452
Adam.

236
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:29,454
You're the man.

237
00:18:29,522 --> 00:18:32,616
You have to start the conversation.
Ask her out. Take her to dinner.

238
00:18:32,692 --> 00:18:35,126
- I can't do that. H-How–
- <i>[ Phone Ringing ]</i>

239
00:18:36,762 --> 00:18:38,696
Hmm.

240
00:18:38,764 --> 00:18:41,494
This jackass locked himself out of his car.

241
00:18:41,567 --> 00:18:43,865
Figures he can cuss me out on the phone.

242
00:18:43,936 --> 00:18:47,428
Well, he ought to be chilled by now.

243
00:18:47,506 --> 00:18:49,736
- [ Grunts ]
- Harlan–

244
00:18:51,177 --> 00:18:53,111
Follow through, young man.

245
00:18:53,179 --> 00:18:55,170
Follow through.

246
00:18:57,550 --> 00:19:00,678
<i>Are you and Mom still going to Barbados this year?</i>

247
00:19:00,753 --> 00:19:03,847
- Well, we're still deciding.
- Oh. Really?

248
00:19:03,923 --> 00:19:07,859
There's a little problem
that has to be dealt with.

249
00:19:07,927 --> 00:19:10,020
- Between you and Mom?
- No, no.

250
00:19:10,096 --> 00:19:12,724
- At the firm.
- Oh.

251
00:19:12,798 --> 00:19:15,426
There was an indictment last March.

252
00:19:15,501 --> 00:19:17,765
There was an indictment of the firm?

253
00:19:17,837 --> 00:19:21,068
No, of me, personally, no less.

254
00:19:21,140 --> 00:19:24,701
It's nothing.
Some junior G-man playing Clarence Darrow.

255
00:19:24,777 --> 00:19:27,211
But there's a trial date now.January 19.

256
00:19:27,279 --> 00:19:30,715
- A trial?
- Yeah, so we have to work
everything out before then.

257
00:19:30,783 --> 00:19:33,081
But bullshit, if you'll excuse the expression...

258
00:19:33,152 --> 00:19:35,086
expands to fill the allotted time...

259
00:19:35,154 --> 00:19:37,088
so now Barbados is up in the air.

260
00:19:37,156 --> 00:19:39,090
[ Whistles ]

261
00:19:39,158 --> 00:19:41,183
Daddy!

262
00:19:41,260 --> 00:19:42,852
Don't worry.

263
00:19:42,928 --> 00:19:45,362
But if you happen to come up
with the next Harry Potter...

264
00:19:45,431 --> 00:19:47,592
we may need it to pay the ganef lawyers.

265
00:19:47,667 --> 00:19:50,158
- <i>Over Friday for dinner, right?</i>
- Yeah.

266
00:19:51,537 --> 00:19:53,334
- I love you, Daddy.
- <i>Love ya!</i>

267
00:19:53,406 --> 00:19:55,374
- <i>[ Cab Door Closes ]</i>
- <i>[ Cab Drives Away ]</i>

268
00:19:55,574 --> 00:19:58,975
## <i>[ Stereo: Woman Singing, Faint ]</i>

269
00:20:18,330 --> 00:20:20,821
<i>[ Footsteps ]</i>

270
00:20:22,802 --> 00:20:25,464
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

271
00:20:27,473 --> 00:20:29,134
<i>[ Adam ]</i>
<i>Beth?</i>

272
00:20:34,747 --> 00:20:36,977
<i>[ Knocking Harder ]</i>

273
00:20:37,049 --> 00:20:38,710
<i>Beth?</i>

274
00:20:39,985 --> 00:20:42,510
Adam!

275
00:20:42,588 --> 00:20:46,524
I'm so sorry.
I just don't feel like any company tonight.

276
00:20:46,592 --> 00:20:48,856
<i>Oh, that's okay.</i>

277
00:20:48,928 --> 00:20:51,920
<i>Come out with me. I wanna show you something.</i>

278
00:20:55,401 --> 00:20:57,062
<i>Beth?</i>

279
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:03,508
- Adam, the park's closed.
- J-Just a little bit further.

280
00:21:03,576 --> 00:21:06,841
- I wanna go back! I'm not–
- Shh-shh-shh. Over here.

281
00:21:15,955 --> 00:21:18,583
- Adam, I–
- Shh-shh-shh!

282
00:21:46,318 --> 00:21:48,946
Raccoon in Central Park?

283
00:22:05,504 --> 00:22:08,837
That was so cool.

284
00:22:08,908 --> 00:22:11,741
What are they doing here?

285
00:22:11,811 --> 00:22:14,041
Foraging.

286
00:22:14,113 --> 00:22:17,048
- How did you know where they'd be?
- They live here.

287
00:22:18,150 --> 00:22:21,051
I used to come and watch them a lot.

288
00:22:21,120 --> 00:22:22,781
It's quiet.

289
00:22:26,392 --> 00:22:32,160
They don't really belong here,
you know, but here they are.

290
00:22:32,231 --> 00:22:36,224
They're coming back around in a little while.
You wanna wait?

291
00:22:37,403 --> 00:22:39,064
Yeah, sure.

292
00:23:11,770 --> 00:23:13,237
[ Gasps ]
Oh. Mr. Klieber.

293
00:23:13,305 --> 00:23:16,240
Yes. That's all right. I startled you.

294
00:23:16,308 --> 00:23:18,606
Yes.

295
00:23:18,677 --> 00:23:22,909
I just wanted to tell you what a good job
you've done for us the last year and a half.

296
00:23:22,982 --> 00:23:25,177
Well, that's good.

297
00:23:25,251 --> 00:23:27,276
When your father explained your–

298
00:23:27,353 --> 00:23:30,345
When he explained your... things...

299
00:23:31,557 --> 00:23:34,492
well, I had my– my doubts,
but, uh, he was right.

300
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:38,428
A man of your background at the salary you're
getting has been a value to this company.

301
00:23:38,497 --> 00:23:40,931
- Well, that's good.
- Yes.

302
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:44,800
But the world is changing.
You can't be the corner candy store anymore.

303
00:23:44,870 --> 00:23:47,498
- You've got to compete.
- Candy store?

304
00:23:47,573 --> 00:23:50,804
5,000 at a hundred, not five at a thousand.

305
00:23:50,876 --> 00:23:53,606
Adam, I've got to let you go.

306
00:23:53,679 --> 00:23:57,137
But I will write you a recommendation
that will knock your socks off.

307
00:23:57,216 --> 00:24:00,151
- L-Let me go?
- I'm truly sorry.

308
00:24:00,219 --> 00:24:02,517
Yeah, but I– I don't wanna go.
I haven't finished.

309
00:24:02,588 --> 00:24:04,988
I have a bid, Adam. It's done.

310
00:24:06,292 --> 00:24:09,125
- You found a better chip?
- <i>Not better.</i>

311
00:24:09,194 --> 00:24:10,889
Cheaper.

312
00:24:10,963 --> 00:24:13,158
Look, go home.

313
00:24:13,232 --> 00:24:15,257
Talk it over with your dad.

314
00:24:15,334 --> 00:24:17,859
- I'm sure he'll find you another job.
- No, my dad–

315
00:24:17,937 --> 00:24:20,997
Kelli has your severance.
It's been a pleasure working with you.

316
00:24:21,073 --> 00:24:25,601
And I mean that sincerely. Good-bye, Adam.

317
00:24:27,246 --> 00:24:29,305
<i>[ Lulu ]</i>
<i>Good-bye, Mr. Klieber.</i>

318
00:24:35,955 --> 00:24:37,946
Adam, dude. Sorry about that, man.

319
00:24:38,023 --> 00:24:41,356
Don't think about it, bro.
Something will come up, man. I promise.

320
00:24:46,999 --> 00:24:48,990
I'm so sorry, Adam.

321
00:24:49,068 --> 00:24:50,797
<i>See you around, okay?</i>

322
00:25:25,437 --> 00:25:28,929
[ Children Chattering, Laughing ]

323
00:25:34,079 --> 00:25:36,013
<i>[ Children Screaming ]</i>

324
00:25:36,081 --> 00:25:38,572
<i>[ Chattering, Laughing Continue ]</i>

325
00:26:05,377 --> 00:26:07,368
<i>[ Engine Stops ]</i>

326
00:26:07,446 --> 00:26:10,711
Excuse me, sir. What are you doing there?

327
00:26:10,783 --> 00:26:13,547
- I said, what you doin'?
- Watching the children.

328
00:26:13,619 --> 00:26:16,315
Uh-huh. Let me have some I.D., sir.

329
00:26:16,388 --> 00:26:18,754
I-I-I was looking at the children.

330
00:26:18,824 --> 00:26:22,191
Sir, turn around.
Put your hands on the fence, please.

331
00:26:22,261 --> 00:26:25,924
- Why–Why are you doing this?
- Lean forward, put your hands on the fence, please.

332
00:26:25,998 --> 00:26:27,795
Turn around!

333
00:26:27,866 --> 00:26:30,300
Hands on the fence.

334
00:26:30,369 --> 00:26:32,303
What–What are you doing?

335
00:26:32,371 --> 00:26:35,306
I'm taking your wallet out of your back pocket
to check your identification, sir.

336
00:26:35,374 --> 00:26:38,741
- 1 5-Adam to Central-K,
I need a name check. Adam Raki.
- Let's go.

337
00:26:38,811 --> 00:26:42,508
- Is this the man you reported?
- I wasn't the one who saw him.

338
00:26:42,581 --> 00:26:44,606
Where do you live, sir?

339
00:26:44,683 --> 00:26:47,117
Please stay where you are.

340
00:26:47,186 --> 00:26:50,280
Do you live or do you have business
in this neighborhood, sir?

341
00:26:50,355 --> 00:26:52,653
Everything's fine. Go on back inside.

342
00:26:52,724 --> 00:26:55,852
- [ Children Chattering ]
- Beth!

343
00:26:55,928 --> 00:26:58,328
- Are you the one who reported this?
- Adam.

344
00:26:58,397 --> 00:27:01,025
- What's going on?
- <i>[ Officer ] You know this man?</i>

345
00:27:01,100 --> 00:27:03,796
Yeah, he's my neighbor. What happened?

346
00:27:03,869 --> 00:27:06,770
- I–
- <i>[ Radio: Dispatcher ]</i>
<i>1 5-Adam. Raki- R-A-K-I. No hits.</i>

347
00:27:06,839 --> 00:27:10,104
- <i>He's clean.</i>
- All right. Sorry about that.

348
00:27:10,175 --> 00:27:12,666
<i>Can't be too careful with kids, right?</i>

349
00:27:12,744 --> 00:27:14,735
You can go.

350
00:27:19,852 --> 00:27:21,843
Adam!

351
00:27:29,228 --> 00:27:30,889
[ Slams ]

352
00:27:43,041 --> 00:27:44,975
- <i>[ Knocking ]</i>
- <i>Adam?</i>

353
00:27:47,713 --> 00:27:50,511
Enough with the presents, okay?

354
00:27:50,582 --> 00:27:53,312
Well, that was kind of awful, wasn't it?

355
00:27:53,385 --> 00:27:58,516
I mean, God, you just stopped by
to watch the kids. I do that for a living.

356
00:28:05,731 --> 00:28:08,894
- Police freak me out too. Okay?
- Do you wanna come in?

357
00:28:10,903 --> 00:28:12,564
Okay.

358
00:28:21,246 --> 00:28:23,305
So, you live alone?

359
00:28:23,382 --> 00:28:25,475
Yes.

360
00:28:25,551 --> 00:28:28,577
I mean, it's– it's big for one person.

361
00:28:29,821 --> 00:28:31,516
For the city.

362
00:28:31,590 --> 00:28:33,683
Well, my father lived here too.

363
00:28:33,759 --> 00:28:35,556
Oh! Where is he now?

364
00:28:35,627 --> 00:28:37,561
- Queens.
- Queens.

365
00:28:37,629 --> 00:28:39,756
He died six weeks ago.

366
00:28:39,831 --> 00:28:42,925
Oh, God. I'm so sorry.

367
00:28:43,001 --> 00:28:46,562
My friend Harlan says Queens
is where everybody goes to die...

368
00:28:46,638 --> 00:28:48,970
because they can't tell the difference.

369
00:28:50,042 --> 00:28:52,977
That's–That's awful.

370
00:28:54,046 --> 00:28:56,071
Harlan said it was a joke.

371
00:28:56,148 --> 00:28:58,912
Oh, I meant about your father.

372
00:28:58,984 --> 00:29:00,645
Uh–

373
00:29:02,888 --> 00:29:06,221
- What about your mother?
- She died when I was eight.

374
00:29:09,328 --> 00:29:11,319
I'm so sorry.

375
00:29:14,733 --> 00:29:18,225
I had a really nice time last night in the park.

376
00:29:20,239 --> 00:29:22,230
Were you excited?

377
00:29:23,542 --> 00:29:26,443
- What?
- Sexually, when we were in the park.

378
00:29:27,512 --> 00:29:32,643
Um– Uh, no, not exactly.

379
00:29:32,718 --> 00:29:36,677
Well, I ask because I was,
and I wondered if you were too.

380
00:29:36,755 --> 00:29:39,155
[ Stammers ]

381
00:29:39,224 --> 00:29:42,159
Thank you so much for the glass of water.

382
00:29:42,227 --> 00:29:45,822
I– I should– I should be going now.

383
00:29:45,897 --> 00:29:48,161
Because I said that thing
about being sexually excited?

384
00:29:48,233 --> 00:29:50,258
No! No, no. I just–

385
00:29:50,335 --> 00:29:52,269
Well– [ Sighs ] yeah.

386
00:29:52,337 --> 00:29:54,430
Oh–

387
00:29:54,506 --> 00:29:57,942
Uh, sometimes i-i-it's hard for me to, um–

388
00:29:59,578 --> 00:30:03,537
<i>I have this thing</i>
<i>that makes it hard to, um- to a-</i>

389
00:30:03,615 --> 00:30:06,914
It's called Asperger's syndrome.

390
00:30:06,985 --> 00:30:08,782
Oh.

391
00:30:14,293 --> 00:30:18,389
One thing about it is not knowing
what people are thinking.

392
00:30:20,032 --> 00:30:21,966
- <i>Like right now.</i>
- Oh. Right.

393
00:30:22,034 --> 00:30:27,529
I guess I was wondering
what that feels like for you.

394
00:30:27,606 --> 00:30:31,235
<i>[ Stammering ]</i>
<i>It doesn't feel like anything. I-It just is.</i>

395
00:30:31,310 --> 00:30:33,471
Okay.

396
00:30:34,780 --> 00:30:36,873
My brain works differently from N.T.'s.

397
00:30:36,948 --> 00:30:39,178
N.T.'s?

398
00:30:39,251 --> 00:30:41,412
Neurotypicals.

399
00:30:41,486 --> 00:30:43,420
Sometimes I can't understand them...

400
00:30:43,488 --> 00:30:46,548
especially when they mean something different
from what they're actually saying.

401
00:30:46,625 --> 00:30:48,490
You don't do that?

402
00:30:48,560 --> 00:30:50,790
No, most Aspies are really honest.

403
00:30:50,862 --> 00:30:53,592
Uh, psychologists think
it's a lack of imagination.

404
00:30:53,665 --> 00:30:56,031
But psychologists are mostly N.T.'s.

405
00:30:56,101 --> 00:31:00,435
Albert Einstein, Thomas Jefferson, Mozart,
they all had lots of imagination.

406
00:31:00,505 --> 00:31:02,871
They had Asperger's?

407
00:31:02,941 --> 00:31:05,068
Probably.

408
00:31:07,312 --> 00:31:09,246
When I was younger...

409
00:31:09,314 --> 00:31:12,249
I would have just thought
you were sexually excited because I was.

410
00:31:12,317 --> 00:31:15,252
That's called mind blindness.

411
00:31:15,320 --> 00:31:18,380
I had to learn to ask
what other people are thinking.

412
00:31:20,992 --> 00:31:23,859
I understand.
[ Chuckles ]

413
00:31:23,929 --> 00:31:26,261
It's okay.

414
00:31:26,331 --> 00:31:28,697
Oh.

415
00:31:28,767 --> 00:31:32,100
I re– I really should go.

416
00:31:32,170 --> 00:31:33,865
Okay.

417
00:31:37,209 --> 00:31:39,609
I'm really sorry about your father.

418
00:31:39,678 --> 00:31:42,169
Oh.

419
00:31:42,247 --> 00:31:44,374
Can I see you again?

420
00:31:45,717 --> 00:31:49,312
Um, well, I'm– I'm right upstairs, so–

421
00:31:49,388 --> 00:31:52,016
Great. Okay. I'll see you.

422
00:31:55,160 --> 00:31:57,390
<i>[ School Bell Rings ]</i>

423
00:31:57,462 --> 00:31:59,396
Hi.

424
00:32:04,469 --> 00:32:06,801
[ Knocks ]

425
00:32:06,872 --> 00:32:09,966
- Do you have a minute?
- Oh, hey, Beth. Sure. Come on in.

426
00:32:10,041 --> 00:32:11,804
Thank you.

427
00:32:11,877 --> 00:32:15,369
Oh, you think it's a bad sign
when the description of a school...

428
00:32:15,447 --> 00:32:17,574
bores its director?

429
00:32:17,649 --> 00:32:20,049
Um–
[ Nervous Chuckle ]

430
00:32:20,118 --> 00:32:23,053
What do you know about Asperger's syndrome?

431
00:32:23,121 --> 00:32:25,055
Oh.

432
00:32:25,123 --> 00:32:29,150
Well, it's a developmental disorder,
kind of a high-functioning autism.

433
00:32:29,227 --> 00:32:31,787
What does that mean exactly?

434
00:32:31,863 --> 00:32:34,798
Well, there's a broad range.
It could be hard to tell.

435
00:32:34,866 --> 00:32:39,462
- It could be severe social interaction problems.
- Uh-huh.

436
00:32:39,538 --> 00:32:42,632
Maybe I should get in on this,
interview the child and we can get some ser–

437
00:32:42,707 --> 00:32:44,641
Oh, no, no. It's my neighbor.

438
00:32:44,709 --> 00:32:46,643
He has it.

439
00:32:46,711 --> 00:32:49,475
But he's really, really sweet...

440
00:32:49,548 --> 00:32:53,348
and kind of interesting.

441
00:32:53,418 --> 00:32:56,785
Yeah, sometimes they can be quite brilliant.

442
00:32:56,855 --> 00:32:59,688
It is on the autism spectrum.

443
00:33:00,792 --> 00:33:03,124
Oh, you know, actually I think I have a–

444
00:33:05,063 --> 00:33:07,588
This is a first-person account.
<i>Pretending to be Normal.</i>

445
00:33:07,666 --> 00:33:11,033
Oh, no, it's– it's not– it's not serious–

446
00:33:11,102 --> 00:33:12,899
- Hmm. Okay.
- Thank you.

447
00:33:12,971 --> 00:33:14,734
Sure.

448
00:33:14,806 --> 00:33:18,367
Oh, Beth? Would you
just take a look at this for me, please?

449
00:33:18,443 --> 00:33:20,070
Sure.

450
00:33:20,145 --> 00:33:24,582
So, you're saying, really,
that he's not prime relationship material.

451
00:33:24,649 --> 00:33:27,743
- Right?
- [ Sighs ] Um–

452
00:33:27,819 --> 00:33:29,684
Not really.

453
00:33:29,754 --> 00:33:32,245
- Well, well, it–
- No. That's okay.

454
00:33:35,594 --> 00:33:37,357
Thanks.

455
00:33:37,562 --> 00:33:41,896
So, um, subtracting your father's liabilities–

456
00:33:41,967 --> 00:33:45,801
uh, credit card debt,
funeral costs, fees, et cetera–

457
00:33:45,871 --> 00:33:50,399
<i>from his assets reduces the, uh- the estate-</i>

458
00:33:50,475 --> 00:33:52,670
roughly, $25,000.

459
00:33:52,744 --> 00:33:56,271
And, uh, he bequeathed $5,000...

460
00:33:56,348 --> 00:33:59,078
<i>to the Kids at Risk Music Fund...</i>

461
00:33:59,150 --> 00:34:01,914
<i>$ 10,000 to you, Mr. Keats.</i>

462
00:34:01,987 --> 00:34:03,420
Oh.

463
00:34:03,488 --> 00:34:07,424
So, as his primary beneficiary, Adam–Adam?

464
00:34:07,492 --> 00:34:09,722
Uh, you inherit the remainder.

465
00:34:09,794 --> 00:34:12,888
<i>That would be the death benefit from Juilliard...</i>

466
00:34:12,964 --> 00:34:15,728
and the funds from the T.I.A.A. retirement plan.

467
00:34:15,800 --> 00:34:20,931
<i>Also, there's approximately</i>
<i>$300,000 worth of equity in the apartment.</i>

468
00:34:21,006 --> 00:34:25,375
- <i>So, assuming you sell,</i>
<i>after closing fees and taxes, et cetera-</i>
- Sell what?

469
00:34:25,443 --> 00:34:29,106
We presumed that you'd be moving
to a smaller place.

470
00:34:29,180 --> 00:34:31,546
Move?

471
00:34:31,616 --> 00:34:34,710
<i>Without your father's income,</i>
<i>the mortgage payments are-</i>

472
00:34:34,786 --> 00:34:36,481
I don't wanna move.

473
00:34:36,555 --> 00:34:38,113
Easy.

474
00:34:38,189 --> 00:34:41,625
Think of it as an opportunity.
You might wanna try a different city.

475
00:34:42,961 --> 00:34:44,895
<i>Uh, Mr. Wardlow...</i>

476
00:34:44,963 --> 00:34:48,626
Adam has never been out of the city
alone in his life.

477
00:34:48,700 --> 00:34:50,827
Uh-huh. Well, uh, closer to home then.

478
00:34:50,902 --> 00:34:55,965
- With the income from your job–
- I don't have a job. I was fired from my job.

479
00:34:56,041 --> 00:35:00,774
<i>Oh. Oh, I'm sorry to hear that. That makes</i>
<i>the equity in the apartment even more valuable.</i>

480
00:35:00,845 --> 00:35:03,575
- Changes like this are hard.
- I won't sell my house.

481
00:35:03,648 --> 00:35:06,344
- Mr. Raki, I–
